</li><li class="sense" htag="li" sensenum="2" id="aim_sng_2" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="grammar" hclass="grammar" htag="span">[uncountable, singular]</span></span> <span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">the action or skill of pointing a weapon at somebody/something</span><ul class="examples" htag="ul" hclass="examples"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">Her aim was good and she hit the lion with her first shot.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">The gunman <span class="cl">took aim</span> <span class="gloss" htag="span" hclass="gloss">(= pointed his weapon)</span> and fired.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">His aim was poor and he missed the target.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">It was a perfect aim and there was no way he would miss.</span></li></ul><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="aim3_unbox_4" unbox="snippet"><span class="box_title">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class="body"><span class="unbox">adjective</span><ul class="collocs_list"><li class="li">careful</li><li class="li">direct</li><li class="li">steady</li><li class="li">…</li></ul><span class="unbox">verb + aim</span><ul class="collocs_list"><li class="li">take</li><li class="li">adjust</li></ul><span class="unbox">preposition</span><ul class="collocs_list"><li class="li">aim at</li></ul><span class="xref_to_full_entry">See <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/aim_1" title=" definition in Collocations
